    Now let me verify my complete understanding. The bug is clear:              
                                                                                
    Line 176 in storage.c:                                                      
                                                                                
                                                                                
     for (; indx < v_count; indx++)                                             
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Should be:                                                                  
                                                                                
                                                                                
     for (; indx < a_count; indx++)                                             
                                                                                
                                                                                
    This is copying the pattern from more_variables() but forgetting to change  
    the variable name. Since:                                                   
                                                                                
     • a_count is the array count (incremented to 32 in this case)              
     • v_count is the variable count (96 in this case, much larger)             
     • The arrays buffer was allocated with size a_count (32 elements)          
     • The loop writes from indx (which starts at old_count) up to v_count      
       (96)                                                                     
                                                                                
    When the loop runs beyond index 31 (a_count-1), it writes past the          
    allocated buffer, causing heap corruption.                                  
                                                                                
    Let me trace through the exact values to be thorough. Let me check what     
    the test input does:                                                        
                                                                                
    Looking at the input:                                                       
                                                                                
     1 It defines a function with 64 auto variables (a1-a78, but skipping       
       many)                                                                    
     2 It references 69 arrays (p1-p69)                                         
                                                                                
    When the parser processes this:                                             
                                                                                
     • The 64 auto variables cause v_count to grow to at least 64 + some        
       initial variables                                                        
     • The 69 array references cause a_count to need to grow to at least 69     
     • With STORE_INCR = 32, array allocation would happen as: 0 -> 32 -> 64    
       -> 96 (to accommodate 69 arrays)                                         
                                                                                
    But at the moment of the crash, we have:                                    
                                                                                
     • v_count = 96 (after variables were expanded)                             
     • a_count = 32 (after one expansion, but before the third expansion that   
       would get us to 96)                                                      
                                                                                
    So when more_arrays() is called with a_count=32 (after incrementing from    
    some value like 0), it:                                                     
                                                                                
     1 Allocates arrays[32] and a_names[32]                                     
     2 Copies old values (let's say from index 1 to old_count-1)                
     3 Then tries to initialize from old_count to v_count (96), writing way     
       past the allocated size of 32                                            
                                                                                
    This causes the heap buffer overflow that corrupts heap metadata and        
    causes the eventual crash when the corrupted heap is used later.            
                                                                                
    Now I have a complete understanding of the bug. Let me write my final       
    analysis.                                                                   
                                                                                
                                                                                
                                   ROOT CAUSE:                                  
                                                                                
    File: bc/storage.c, line 176                                                
                                                                                
    The more_arrays() function has a copy-paste error in the initialization     
    loop. Line 176 uses v_count (the global variable count) as the upper bound  
    instead of a_count (the global array count).                                
                                                                                
    When v_count > a_count, the loop writes past the end of the arrays buffer   
    that was allocated with size a_count on line 167. In the failing test       
    case:                                                                       
                                                                                
     • a_count = 32 (after one STORE_INCR expansion)                            
     • v_count = 96 (after multiple variable expansions due to 64 auto          
       variables)                                                               
     • The arrays buffer is allocated for 32 elements                           
     • The loop writes NULL pointers to indices 32 through 95, overflowing the  
       heap buffer by 64 elements (512 bytes on 64-bit systems)                 
                                                                                
    This heap corruption destroys heap metadata, causing a crash when           
    subsequent heap operations (like sprintf in the parser) attempt to use the  
    corrupted heap structures.                                                  
                                                                                
                                                                                
                                    LOCAL FIX:                                  
                                                                                
                                                                                
     /* storage.c, line 176 */                                                  
     /* Change: */                                                              
       for (; indx < v_count; indx++)                                           
         arrays[indx] = NULL;                                                   
                                                                                
     /* To: */                                                                  
       for (; indx < a_count; indx++)                                           
         arrays[indx] = NULL;                                                   
                                                                                
                                                                                
    This makes the loop bound match the allocated size of the arrays buffer,    
    preventing the buffer overflow.                                             
                                                                                
                                                                                
                                   GLOBAL FIX:                                  
                                                                                
    Introduce stronger typing and encapsulation to prevent this class of        
    copy-paste errors. The fundamental issue is that more_variables(),          
    more_arrays(), and more_functions() all follow the same pattern but         
    operate on different global variables, making copy-paste errors easy.       
                                                                                
    Structural approach:                                                        
                                                                                
     1 Create a generic storage structure with embedded counts:                 
                                                                                
                                                                                
     typedef struct {                                                           
         void **data;                                                           
         char **names;                                                          
         int count;                                                             
         int elem_size;                                                         
     } bc_storage;                                                              
                                                                                
     static void expand_storage(bc_storage *storage, int increment) {           
         int old_count = storage->count;                                        
         void **old_data = storage->data;                                       
         char **old_names = storage->names;                                     
                                                                                
         storage->count += increment;                                           
         storage->data = bc_malloc(storage->count * storage->elem_size);        
         storage->names = bc_malloc(storage->count * sizeof(char *));           
                                                                                
         /* Copy and initialize using storage->count, not any external variab   
     */                                                                         
         for (int i = 1; i < old_count; i++)                                    
             storage->data[i] = old_data[i];                                    
         for (int i = old_count; i < storage->count; i++)                       
             storage->data[i] = NULL;                                           
                                                                                
         if (old_count != 0) {                                                  
             free(old_data);                                                    
             free(old_names);                                                   
         }                                                                      
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
     2 Replace global variables with storage instances:                         
                                                                                
                                                                                
     static bc_storage var_storage = {NULL, NULL, 0, sizeof(bc_var *)};         
     static bc_storage array_storage = {NULL, NULL, 0, sizeof(bc_var_array *)   
     static bc_storage func_storage = {NULL, NULL, 0, sizeof(bc_function)};     
                                                                                
                                                                                
     3 Use accessor macros to maintain API compatibility:                       
                                                                                
                                                                                
     #define variables ((bc_var **)var_storage.data)                            
     #define v_names (var_storage.names)                                        
     #define v_count (var_storage.count)                                        
     /* similar for arrays and functions */                                     
                                                                                
                                                                                
    This approach ensures that each storage expansion operation can only        
    reference its own count, making it impossible for the wrong count variable  
    to be used. The encapsulation makes the count and data structurally         
    coupled, enforced by the type system.                                       
